{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"46566cb6-6d94-44ae-9141-6ad12be7a11d","content":"**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work without `unsafe`:\n\n```csharp\nSpan<nint>  a = stackalloc nint[4];   // ✅\nSpan<nuint> b = stackalloc nuint[3];  // ✅\n```\n\nOn this 64-bit system, `nint` is 8 bytes, so `a[1]` holds `long.MaxValue` (9223372036854775807) as expected. Native-sized integers have been stackalloc-compatible since C# 9 / .NET 5.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"07136317-f5c0-48b1-8b6e-448eb69f9178","outputTokens":161,"requestId":"FE00:2280B0:13B134B:1613FF6:6A066FAF"},"id":"16e917bd-e4b9-42b8-9032-8ad5107e62e0","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:58:29.154Z","parentId":"6c668f7b-7e24-4a10-ac65-02f8c49260b2"}
